# Conjectures of the Theory of Entropicity (ToE)

The Theory of Entropicity (ToE) is an emerging, non-mainstream conceptual framework in theoretical physics formulated by independent researcher John Onimisi Obidi. It flips the traditional hierarchy of physics by postulating that entropy is not a secondary statistical byproduct of matter, but the fundamental, real, and dynamical field (S(x)) from which all reality emerges. [1, 2, 3]
The core architectural backbone of this theory relies on three cascading pillars known as Obidi's Three Conjectures. [1]

1. Obidi's First Conjecture (The Ontological Pillar)
Premise: Entropy is the foundational universal field from which all reality, including matter and energy, emerges. [1]

2. Obidi's Second Conjecture (The Dynamical Pillar)
Premise: Physical laws and force interactions are derived from the underlying Entropic Field, rendering phenomena like gravity as emergent. [1]

Obidi’s Third Conjecture completes the hierarchical framework of the Theory of Entropicity (ToE) by defining the nature of the physical arena itself. [1] 
The Third Conjecture: Emergent Geometry
Statement: Physical spacetime emerges from a deeper entropic-informational manifold. [1] 
Core Concept: Space, time, curvature, and the spacetime metric are not fundamental primitives. They are macroscopic manifestations of underlying entropic-informational relations. [1] 
The Paradigm Shift: Traditional modern physics treats spacetime as a pre-existing container where events happen. The Third Conjecture reverses this, arguing that spacetime geometry is an output generated by the organization of the deeper entropic manifold. [1, 2] 
The Complete Hierarchical Architecture of ToE
Together, the three Obidi Conjectures form a complete, top-down structure for reality: [1] 
The First Conjecture (Ontology): Entropy is the fundamental universal field of nature.
The Second Conjecture (Dynamics): All physical interactions and laws (gravity, quantum mechanics, gauge forces) derive from this Entropic Field.
The Third Conjecture (Geometry): Spacetime itself emerges from the entropic-informational structure. [1, 3] 
