The Theory of Entropicity (ToE), introduced by physicist John Onimisi Obidi, is an emerging theoretical framework in physics that posits entropy is not merely a statistical measure of disorder, but the fundamental ontological substrate from which all physical phenomena, including space, time, and gravity, emerge. [1, 2]

Core Conjectures of ToE
The architecture of the Theory of Entropicity is built upon several foundational conjectures that invert the traditional hierarchy of physics: [1, 2, 3]
The Obidi Conjecture (Ontological Primacy of Entropy): Entropy is the primary physical field of the universe (S(x)). Instead of space and time forming the background of physical reality, the geometric, quantum, and material realities are emergent manifestations of the underlying entropic field's gradients and curvature. [1, 2]
The Obidi Equivalence Principle (OEP): This principle establishes "entropic-geometric duality". It postulates that spacetime geometry is fundamentally a macroscopic projection of a deeper information-geometric manifold, meaning gravity is essentially an emergent entropic pressure rather than a fundamental force. [1]
The Obidi Action Principle (OAP): The variational framework mathematically governing the universe's dynamics. It asserts that existence is "entropic motion," where physical systems evolve along paths that maximize distinguishability. [1, 2]

Key Theorems and Postulates
Derived from these conjectures are a series of supporting postulates and theorems that define the limits and mechanics of the universe: [1, 2, 3]
The "No-Rush" Theorem: This theorem establishes a universal lower bound on interaction durations, meaning state synchronizations and physical changes cannot occur instantaneously. Under this framework, the speed of light (c) is reinterpreted as the maximum rate at which the entropic field can physically reorganize itself and redistribute information. [1, 2]
Entropic Potential: This measure defines a system's capacity to generate complexity. It reframes the early universe not as a state of maximum, chaotic entropy, but as a state of maximum "Entropic Potential," which steadily cashed in its gradients to drive the structured complexity we observe today. [1]
Dethroning the Observer: Unlike some interpretations of quantum mechanics where the observer plays a privileged, reality-shaping role, ToE embeds the observer as a localized subsystem entirely constrained by the pre-computed dynamics of the overarching entropic field. [1]
